There is nothing analytic behind this, but in watching the CME's FedWatch trends, and reading blogs written by Fed watchers, I think a move towards higher rates in the next five weeks is extremely unlikely, and a move towards lower rates is only a tiny bit more likely. Members of the Fed have said over and over again that they see stability, and even though Jerome Powell's post-meeting remarks seemed to crack the door a bit for a rate change at some point down the road, I think it's unlikely to happen this soon.
Economy still stable. Barring significant earnings surprises, likely to remain.

Why would the Fed raise rates? Because the economy is heating too quickly. This does not seem to be the case as (a) GDP growth is positive but moderate, and (b) inflation is holding steady despite great employment figures. Furthermore, after the pounding the Fed took last year from Trump when they raised rates, and with Trump recently saying at Davos that he could get used to negative rates, it's just hard to imagine the Fed raising them except under the most dire of circumstances.
Thanks to the magic of hedonic adjustments, CPI remains at a nice level. Economy still doing fine. They'll take the path of least resistance.
